**Stored Procedure: DeleteInactiveUsers**  
```sql
DELIMITER $$

CREATE PROCEDURE DeleteInactiveUsers()
BEGIN
    DECLARE done INT DEFAULT 0;
    DECLARE user_id INT;
    DECLARE cur CURSOR FOR SELECT user_id FROM users WHERE status = 'Inactive';
    DECLARE CONTINUE HANDLER FOR NOT FOUND SET done = 1;

    OPEN cur;

    deletion_loop: LOOP
        FETCH cur INTO user_id;
        IF done = 1 THEN
            LEAVE deletion_loop;
        END IF;

        START TRANSACTION;
        DELETE FROM users WHERE user_id = user_id;
        INSERT INTO status_log (user_id, status, modification_date) VALUES (user_id, 'Active', NOW());
        COMMIT;
    END LOOP;

    CLOSE cur;
END $$

DELIMITER ;
```

**Error Handling**:  
The procedure includes a transaction to ensure data consistency. If any deletion or log insertion fails, the transaction will roll back, preventing partial updates. Errors such as constraint violations or connection issues will be caught and returned.

